<br>
Yes the current judicial system is flawed, allowing the innocent to be jailed and the guilty to walk free, but when you look at the fact that the United states has the highest incarceration rate in the world, something has to be done.<br>
one out of every 147 people ( as of june 99) are incarcerated at a yearly cost of 40,000 per year for a normal meduim security inmate. WHen you add in maximum security, death row, and those individuals who are elderly of sick, the costs can rise to over 100,000 per year.<br>
<br>
Now 40k a year to put someone in jail is more than the average household makes. Why should I as an American provide food and shelter for someone who is not a productive member of our society? Why should some sicko who rapes and murders little children be provided with 3 meals a day, an excersize program, free medical care, and a permenant roof over his head?<br>
<br>
What is the theory behind incarcerating someone for life? Why do we pay to keep someone in prison until they die? What is the point? Why do we not excecute them in the beginning and spend the 2-5 million dollars on worthwile social programs? <br>
<br>
If you think about it, a 25 year old who is convicted of multiple homicides and is sentenced to life imprisonment without the possibility of parole, will be incarcerated for 55+ until the natural end of his life at age 80. At 40k a year, thats 2.2 million dollars and will likely be more since as he gets older he will need more medical procedures that we will pay for. And since he is spending his life with other males who are spending their life in jail, at some point in time, he will either consent sex, or be raped by someone. This someone could very well give him the aids virus wich will increase his yearly cost to upwards of 100k a year as the disease progresses.<br>
<br>
What could the american people do with the money saved? How many social programs can we fund with that money? How many drug rehab centers, homeless shelters, victim assistance centers, and education programs can we fund with the money we would save by not keeping people in jail for life? Think about it. 2-5 million per prisioner. In fact, if you just look at the 4781 currently incarcerated in fedearl prisons for life, thats 191 million dollars. And thats just federal prisons which hold less than 10% of the prisoner population.<br>
In that same 10% for federal prisons, there are an additional 12,699 who are sentenced to more than 20 years. Thats another 500 million we could save by broadening the death penalty, just in federal prisons.<br>
<br>
If we look at a system without the death penalty we get people who spend the majority of their lives in prison and get out and have nothing to do. A 20 year old who goes to jail for 25 years gets out when he is 45. A 45 year old man with no work experience, a criminal record, and most likely lacking a college degree is going to find it hard to get a job. What choices does a person in that position have in order to survive? THe most likely course for him would be to revert to a life of crime in order to survive, or to get back into jail so he can eat and have a roof over his head.  <br>
<br>
In the least I feel that murderers should recieve the death penalty. If you take someones life other than in self defense, your life should be forfiet pure and simple.<br>
<br>
I also feel that any sentence greater than 15 years should be a death sentence, especially those who get sentence to life imprisonment and definately those who will never be parolled.<br>
